<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-08-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-08-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="733" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d733">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1054</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 363]</seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-08-10">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 10, 1915</hi>.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your
                                despatch No. 394 of April 14, 1915,<note n="1" xml:id="d733fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_373">p.
                                    373</ref>.</note> in regard to possible plans for rendering the
                                shipping from America to neutral countries less hazardous than it is
                                at present.</p>
                            <p>The Department does not perceive any objection to your suggesting a
                                meeting of shipping interests, provided, of course, you act entirely
                                unofficially in bringing it about. As to subsequent participation or
                                recognition by this Government, even unofficially, the proposals or
                                plans resulting from the meeting would have to be considered. In
                                case you undertake to set on foot such a meeting, the <pb facs="0764" n="506" xml:id="pg_506"/> Department desires that
                                you make it clear that you act merely in an advisory capacity and in
                                no respect officially.</p>
                            <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                            <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilbur J. Carr</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>